{"word":"παλαιόω","slug":"παλαιόω","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>παλαιόω</b></el> <el>(πᾰλαιόω,) </el><br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b><a href='S:παλαιός'><el>παλαιός</el></a>\n<p/><div class='li500'><b>I. </b><i>to make old</i>, mostly in <a href='S:passive signification'><a href='S:Passive Voice'>Pass.</a></a> (<a href='S:present tense'>pres.</a>) <i>to be old</i> or <i>antiquated</i>, <el>βραχίονος π.</el> <i>is of long standing</i>, <b><a href='S:Hippocrates'>Hipp.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>II. </b>in <a href='S:passive signification'><a href='S:Passive Voice'>Pass.</a></a> also, <i>to become old</i>, <b><a href='S:Plato'>Plat.</a></b><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>III. </b>like <a href='S:Latin'>Lat.</a> <el>antiquare, to abrogate</el> a law, <b><a href='S:New Testament'>NTest.</a></b><p/></div>"}]}